I understand your urgency. Let’s make some quick fixes directly in your code. Here’s an example of how you could apply the changes. Suppose your component looks something like this:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
  const [info, setInfo] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (data) {
      setInfo(data.info);
    }
  }, [data]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{data.title}</h1>
      <p>{info.description}</p>
      <ul>
        {data.items.map(item => (
          <li key={item.id}>{item.name}</li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export default MyComponent;
```

### Quick Fix:

Modify your component with the following defensive checks:

```jsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

const MyComponent = ({ data }) => {
  const [info, setInfo] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    if (data) {
      setInfo(data.info || {});
    }
  }, [data]);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{data?.title || 'Default Title'}</h1>
      <p>{info?.description || 'Default Description'}</p>
      <ul>
        {data?.items?.map(item => (
          <li key={item?.id || Math.random()}>{item?.name || 'Default Name'}</li>
        )) || <li>No items available</li>}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
};

export default MyComponent;
```

### Changes Made:

1. **Optional Chaining:** Use `data?.title`, `info?.description`, and `data?.items?.map` to safely access these properties.
2. **Default Values:** Provided default text ('Default Title', 'Default Description', 'Default Name') to display if the data is not available.
3. **Fallback for Empty Arrays:** Added a fallback message for when `data.items` is undefined or empty.

Applying these changes should prevent runtime errors related to accessing properties of `undefined`. Once your demo is over, consider revisiting these changes for more robust error handling and better data validation.
